Description: Used widely in the North Island of New Zealand to constrain the age of marine terraces. The tephra has been subject to various direct and indirect chronological techniques, including isotopic, radiometric, radiation exposure, and stratigraphic approaches. Results of dating methods applied since 2012 are summarized here. Publications before this date may have associated a different age to the tephra.

 Flude and Storey 2016
 Ryan et al., 2020

Dating technique: surface exposure dating using the cosmogenic nuclides 10Be and 26Al
Description:
Six samples were taken from this site; all but one from boulders: WC02_11A, WC02_11B; WC02_13; WC02_14; WC02_15; WC02_12 (not boulder). 
Age determined from both 10Be and 26Al; however only 10Be ages provided for all samples. The 10Be and 26Al ages overlapped (with error) in 3 of 4 instances. Of the six samples, there was one outlier - this includes a 26Al result.
An average of the 10Be ages is provided here. Result details are provided in Table 1.

Description:
This is a wood sample from the massive mud facies of the sands from the islands III (Paranaguá, Brazil). It provided an age >40 000 years B.P,  This result was corrected by the natural isotopic fractionation (-25%). The error was +/- 1 σ (68.3% probability). 
According to the calculated age and the chronostratigraphy of the region, a date of the deposit with late Pleistocene ages is assumed. Representing an RSL indicator during the last interglacial.
Reference(s):
Branco et al., 2010
 Rubio-Sandoval et al., 2021

Description:
This is a wood sample from the massive mud facies of the sands from an outcrop of the Canal do Varadouro  (Paranaguá, Brazil) that is older than the detection of the method (>40 000 B.P). The wooden fragment comes from a tidal paleo-channel full of sand, fine and abundant plant remains. 
According to the calculated age and the chronostratigraphy of the region, a date of the deposit with late Pleistocene ages is assumed. Representing an RSL indicator during the last interglacial.
Reference(s):
Angulo et al., 2002
 Rubio-Sandoval et al., 2021

Description:
Sr isotope ratios were measured at two laboratories, the University of Cambridge
and the University of the Ryukyus, using a VG Sector 54 and a Finnigan Mat 262
mass spectrometer. The 88Sr beam was controlled at ca. 3 V during which 12 blocks
of 10 ratios were measured. Each sample was analysed one to three times. The
Rb content was low enough (less than 0.1 ppm) that no correction for in-growth of
radiogenic 87Sr was necessary. A 85Rb beam was monitored for within run correction.
Typical corrections of 0.000 005 were required to the measured 87Sr/86Sr ratios. Mass fractionation was corrected using an exponential fractionation law. The NBS SRM
987 standard measured during the course of this study gave 87Sr/86Sr = 0.710 251
(±9, 2SD) (n = 42) at Cambridge and 87Sr/86Sr = 0.710 246 (±9, 2SD) (n = 25)
at Ryukyu. Measurements of 87Sr/86Sr in a modern coral standard from Minamidaito-
jima gave 0.709 178 (±10, 2SD) (n = 17) and 0.709 175 (±9, 2SD) (n = 15),
respectively. The data were normalized to 86Sr/88Sr = 0.1194 and to 87Sr/86Sr =
0.709 18 for the coral standard, which was analysed in each turret (or magazine) of
samples.
Reference(s):
Ohde et al. 2002
 Hallmann et al., 2021

Description:

Marine shell fragment in marine silt and clay. The age is considered to be a minimum age, possibly MIS 5 in age.
Comments/details on MIS designation: Though the age is finite, it is considered to be a minimum age and older than MIS 3.
Reference(s): McNeely, 2002

Description:
GSC-1475: >37000 yr BP

Sample was whole shells of Hiatella Arctica. The outer fraction (outer 21-60%) produced a finite age (38200+/-2000), while the more reliable inner fraction was infinite.
Comments/details on MIS designation: The radiocarbon age is infinite, so older than MIS 3.
Reference(s): Blake, 1988

Description: The age of the basal glacial till was interpreted to be Illinoisan (MIS 6) based on regional correlations of the depth of till unit. The thickness and character of the marine sediments were such that they thought a later substage of MIS 5 was not likely. Pollen in the upper parts of the marine unit indicate an environment that is warmer than present. They felt it was unlikely to be older than MIS 5e
Comments/details on MIS designation: No direct dating of the unit have been done.
Reference(s): Occhietti et al., 1995

Description:
Several radiocarbon dates give minimum ages of the marine unit.

GSC-2313 - plant detritus - >38 ka
BGS-259 - wood - >35 ka
GSC-4633 HP - marine shell fragments - 42.9 ± 0.72 ka

Pollen, diatom, beetle and marine fossils indicate that the sediments were deposited when there was warmer than present conditions. Specifically, fossils of oysters were found, indicating warmer water conditions, which rule out a MIS 3 assignment and making an MIS 5e assignment more likely. Overlying the marine unit is a terrestrial unit that has a pollen assemblage similar to present, indicating cooling conditions. These sediments are covered by Wisconsin till.
Comments/details on MIS designation: Minimum ages of radiocarbon dates and environmental conditions indicate the deposit is older than MIS 3.
Reference(s):
Dredge et al., 1992
 McNeely and McCuaig, 1991
 Prest et al., 1976

Dating technique: Correlation based upon physical characteristics including, but not limited to: sediments, pollen, altitude above modern sea level, and position within a terrace sequence. With regards to the latter, terrace age can be further refined to substages within MIS 5; i.e. MIS 5e, 5c, 5a.\r\n

Description:
Subglacial and aerial volcanic rocks contained in units that predate the deglaciation of Iceland prior to marine sedimentation in the Eemian (Ranga Formation). There are five dates associated with this unit. The ages are as follows:

- Litlilækur Ranga, ISLN-84 aerial lava (K-Ar): 155 +/- 25 ka
- Ljósufjöll (Gerðuberg, Snæfellness), ISLN-46, aerial lava (K-Ar): 135 +/-5 ka
- Prestahnúkur (Langjökull), subglacial (Ar/Ar): 132 +/- 19 ka
- Ljósufjöll (Nykuhraum, Snæfellness), ISLN-99, aerial lava (K-Ar): 129+/-4 ka
- Ljósufjöll summit (Snæfellness), 02/102,L13,U5, subglacial (Ar/Ar): 129+/-16
Comments/details on MIS designation: Dates rocks and sediments that correlate with the Saalian (MIS 6) glaciation
Reference(s):
Clay et al., 2014
 Flude et al., 2008
 Van Vliet-Lanoe et al., 2018

Description: Based on the comparative analysis of modern brown bears (specifically brown bears located on islands in Alaska) and modern polar bears, the polar bear fossil found in interglacial sediments was found to be genetically close to the most recent common ancestor of both brown and polar bears. The most recent common ancestor of polar bears and the Alaskan island brown bears was about 152 ka, while the mean age for all polar bears was 134 ka. It was estimated the fossil bear lived about 10-30 thousand years from the branching point, consistent with an Eemian age assignment.
Reference(s): Lindqvist et al., 2010

Analysis of pollen from this soil indicates plant species that are not found in this region at present and indicates a warmer climate. The radiocarbon date was finite, but was regarded as a minimum age.

Description:
Extensive distribution and abundance throughout Australia during MIS 5e has been severely constricted during the Holocene allowing for the species to be considered an indicator species of MIS 5e around much (but not all) of the continent. There is limited presence of the species during MIS 7.
Although present in the NZ fossil record for MIS 11, 9, 7, and 5e, the species has since become extinct in NZ. It is not considered an indicator species for MIS 5e within NZ, but for Middle to Late Pleistocene interglacials.
Comments/details on MIS designation: This age indication is confined only to Australia.
Reference(s): Murray-Wallace et al., 2000
